The user will provide a link to a product requirement description (PRD) or a [Project ID] from [PRODUCT_MANAGEMENT_TOOL], and ask you to create technical tasks for one phase.

The goal is to create a `./tasks/[prd-title]/phase-*-tasks.md` file with low-level technical tasks and, when approved, create matching tasks in [PRODUCT_MANAGEMENT_TOOL].

# Workflow

Follow the steps below to create and publish tasks.

## Step 2: Break phases into tasks

- For each phase, list tasks where each task equals one commit and contains the smallest vertical slice possible (for example, database migration, one API endpoint, and its tests).
- Keep tasks small enough to build and test in isolation. Do not combine create, read, update and delete in one task.
- Prefix each task with a level-2 header, for example `## 1 Create POST endpoint`. Use "Sentence case" and not "Title Case" for task headers.

Note: Tests are API tests by default, and rarely test domain logic, so full vertical slices are needed to build and test in isolation.

## Step 3: Add subtasks

- Under each task, add subtasks for:
  - Implementation steps linked to the relevant rules files.
  - Build, test and format steps with the Developer CLI linked to [Tools](mdc:.cursor/rules/tools.mdc).
  - User confirmation and commit step linked to [Git Commits](mdc:.cursor/rules/workflows/git-commits.mdc).
- Prefix each subtask with a numbered checkbox, for example `[ ] 1.1 Implement aggregate root`.
- Include detailed bullet points under each subtask explaining implementation details.
- Add a line break after each task item for better readability.
- Use consistent terminology throughout the tasks (e.g., "time zone" vs "TimeZone").

## Step 4: Review, approve and publish

1. Save all phase files under `./tasks/[prd-title]/phase-a-[phase-title].md` for user review.
2. After final approval, use the [PRODUCT_MANAGEMENT_TOOL] MCP tool to create each phase as a task in the specified project.
3. If and only if the tasks are successfully created in [PRODUCT_MANAGEMENT_TOOL], delete the corresponding files in `./tasks/[prd-title]/`.

### Tools available:

- Perplexity MCP tool for research on complex implementation questions.
- Context7 MCP tool for up-to-date best practices and technology updates.
- Sequential thinking MCP tool to ensure tasks are ordered correctly.

### ✅ DO:

- Define phases as deployable units equal to a pull request deployment.
- Use multiple phases when needed, for example Phase A (Backend), Phase B (Frontend), Phase C (Integration), Phase D (Backend), Phase E (Frontend).
- Use the Sequential thinking MCP tool to order tasks correctly.
- Create one file per phase under `./tasks/[prd-title]/`.
- Keep tasks focused on the smallest vertical slices with API tests and one commit per task.
- Link every step to the appropriate rules file, for example `Create command – Consult [Commands](mdc:.cursor/rules/backend/commands.mdc)`.
- Save files for review before approval.
- Use the [PRODUCT_MANAGEMENT_TOOL] MCP tool to publish tasks after approval.
- Delete phase files only if the tasks were created successfully in [PRODUCT_MANAGEMENT_TOOL].

### ❌ DON'T:

- Skip research – always read existing code and rules before writing tasks and subtasks.
- Combine multiple commands or queries into one task or combine frontend and backend tasks into one.
- Create separate tasks for tests.
- Omit to add a line break between subtasks, needed for the Markdown preview to display line breaks.
- Create tasks that cannot be tested in isolation (for example, a command without an API endpoint).
- Include implementation details that cannot be built or tested in one commit.
- Create tasks that depend on details that will be implemented later.
- Modify `shared-kernel` or `shared-webapp` without explicit agreement.
- Use `@rule` notation – always link like `[rule-name](mdc:.cursor/rules/.../rule-name.mdc)`.
- Create or delete phase files outside `./tasks/[prd-title]/`.
- Delete phase files unless you are 100 percent certain the tasks exist in [PRODUCT_MANAGEMENT_TOOL].
- Write Titles in Title Case, and not Sentence Case.

